// system.wit - the WIT trial for the system IDL (milestone M25).
//
// Per the concept ("Decide after a real trial, not in advance"), before choosing
// an IDL we write the real system interfaces in WIT and see where WIT chafes for a
// capability microkernel's Channel IPC. This file is that trial: Log, Storage.Volume,
// Process, a Channel with handle passing, and an EventStream with backpressure
// (plus Transfer across volumes). The chafe analysis and the resulting decision are
// recorded at the bottom.
//
// WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types) was designed for the WASM component model, not
// for a kernel's raw Channel IPC with capabilities and zero-copy shared buffers, so
// the points where the mapping is awkward are annotated inline with `// CHAFE:`.

package liber:system@0.1.0;

// Logs: structured records (the journald model), queryable, rendered as text/JSON/CBOR.
interface log {
	enum severity {
		trace,
		debug,
		info,
		warn,
		error,
		fatal,
	}

	record log-record {
		ts: u64,
		severity: severity,
		source: string,
		fields: list<tuple<string, string>>,
	}

	enum format {
		text,
		json,
		cbor,
	}

	// One-way: emit a record into the journal.
	emit: func(record: log-record);

	// Request/response: query the journal, rendered in `fmt`.
	// CHAFE: the reply is a rendered byte blob. WIT `list<u8>` is copied through the
	// canonical ABI; our query reply is a zero-copy shared buffer (a MemoryObject
	// capability), which WIT cannot express.
	query: func(fmt: format, min-severity: severity) -> list<u8>;
}

// Storage: open/stat/watch files on a vol:// volume (the concept's headline example).
interface storage-volume {
	// A path is a list of validated segments, not a string (no `..`/`/` traversal).
	type relative-path = list<string>;

	record file-info {
		size: u64,
		is-dir: bool,
	}

	enum file-event {
		created,
		modified,
		removed,
	}

	variant error {
		not-found,
		denied,
		gone,
	}

	// CHAFE: a FileHandle is a kernel capability (a MemoryObject / Channel handle the
	// client maps or calls). WIT models opaque handles as `resource` with own/borrow
	// move semantics, which do NOT capture rights attenuation, badges, or transferring
	// a capability to the *peer* over the Channel - the core of our security model.
	resource file-handle {
		// read a chunk; CHAFE again: zero-copy would hand back a shared buffer, not a copy.
		read: func(len: u64) -> list<u8>;
	}

	open: func(path: relative-path, rights: u32) -> result<file-handle, error>;
	stat: func(path: relative-path) -> result<file-info, error>;

	// CHAFE: Watch returns an event stream. WIT `stream<T>` is part of the still-
	// unstable async component-model proposal and assumes that runtime; our streams are
	// one-way Channels read with the kernel `wait` primitive, with backpressure from the
	// bounded queue. The shapes do not line up.
	watch: func(path: relative-path) -> stream<file-event>;

	// CHAFE: Transfer hands a capability across volumes. In WIT this is moving a
	// `resource` between interfaces; it cannot express "transfer the capability over the
	// Channel, attenuated, to another service".
	transfer: func(src: relative-path, dst: borrow<storage-volume>, dst-path: relative-path) -> result<_, error>;
}

// Process lifecycle.
interface process {
	type process-id = u64;

	record spawn-request {
		image: string,
		args: list<string>,
	}

	spawn: func(req: spawn-request) -> result<process-id, string>;
	wait: func(pid: process-id) -> s32; // exit code
	kill: func(pid: process-id);
}

// A Channel with handle passing - the primitive the whole system is built on.
interface channel {
	// CHAFE: this is the heart of the mismatch. Sending a *handle* (a capability) is a
	// first-class kernel operation (handle transfer with rights + badge). WIT has no
	// notion of a transferable kernel handle in a message; `resource` own/borrow is a
	// host-side ownership model, not a wire-level capability transfer.
	send: func(bytes: list<u8>, handle: option<u32>);
	recv: func() -> tuple<list<u8>, option<u32>>;
}

// An event stream with explicit backpressure (the EventStream the IPC model layers on
// top of a bounded Channel: a one-way stream the consumer drains with `wait`).
interface event-stream {
	record event {
		seq: u64,
		payload: list<u8>,
	}

	// CHAFE: backpressure here is the bounded Channel queue returning WOULD_BLOCK and a
	// refund on receive (a kernel/IPC mechanism). WIT `stream` models backpressure inside
	// the async runtime, which we do not have and do not want in the kernel.
	subscribe: func() -> stream<event>;
}

// ===========================================================================
// Chafe summary (where WIT does not fit our system IPC):
//
//  1. Capability / handle passing. The system is built on transferring kernel
//     handles (capabilities) over Channels, with rights attenuation and badges. WIT
//     models opaque handles as `resource` with own/borrow move semantics on the host
//     side; it has no wire-level "transfer this capability to the peer, attenuated".
//     This is the same reason Fuchsia built FIDL rather than reuse an existing IDL.
//
//  2. Zero-copy shared buffers. Our reads and log queries hand back a MemoryObject
//     capability the client maps - no copy. WIT's canonical ABI copies `list<u8>`
//     by value; there is no zero-copy buffer type.
//
//  3. Streams with backpressure. Our EventStreams are one-way Channels drained with
//     the kernel `wait` primitive, backpressured by the bounded queue. WIT `stream<T>`
//     is the unstable async component-model proposal tied to that runtime.
//
//  4. ABI stability. WIT's binary form is the WASM canonical ABI (a lowering for
//     components), not a stable wire layout for raw Channel messages. We need our own
//     stable, versioned binary IPC layout.
//
//  5. Tooling. `wit-bindgen` generates bindings for WASM components, not for our
//     Channel IPC + handle table, so we would not get usable bindings out of it anyway.
//
// Decision (recorded from this trial, M25):
//   Use our OWN IDL with WIT-inspired types and interfaces (records, enums, variants,
//   results, lists, tuples, options), and our OWN binary backend + generators. The IDL
//   carries first-class notions WIT lacks: `handle` (a transferable capability with
//   rights), `buffer` (a zero-copy shared buffer), and `stream` (a wait-drained one-way
//   Channel). When the WASI host arrives (M28) we can still emit WIT *types* for the
//   Wasm boundary, but the system IPC backend is ours. This matches the concept's
//   "likely compromise" (WIT types, our own binary layout + handle table) - confirmed
//   here by practice, not assumed.
// ===========================================================================
